<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-731-668  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 731 668.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Oct 2 1989 n437 p32(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CASE closed. (why more corporations aren't using computer-aidedsoftware engineering) (Soft Talk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Evan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>CASE is not prevalent in large corporations because softwareengineers view it as a means of automation that threatens theirjob security.andP;  Commonly held views are that CASE is hard to learn,stifles developers' creativity, and is not cost-effective.andO;Two-thirds of all Fortune 500 companies do not use CASE products.andO;A market research survey shows that top managers favor CASE muchmore than the middle managers who would be working with thesoftware: 65 percent of top management respond that the CASEproducts they have purchased are fair, good or excellent; only 28percent of lower-level managers answer similarly.andP;  Resistance tothe technology has not stopped IBM or DEC from entering themarket.andP;  IBM will soon introduce a variety of CASE products, whileDEC will integrate diverse CASE tools, making the technologyeasier to use.andP;  Whether corporations will pay attention is the bigquestion.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided Software EngineeringCompaniesSoftware SelectionProgrammingAutomationJob SecuritySoftware PublishersMarket Penetration.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>